Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

In [141]:

We see that the rating column has some entries as "Not given", which are essentially missing ratings. However, the "Not given" string is causing Python to treat the entire rating column as dtype=object. This will prevent us from properly exploring the rating column in the future. Therefore, I am choosing to replace "Not given" values with NaN.

In [142]:

Alternate way: Finding minimum, average, and maximum times individually¶

In [168]:
def min_sec_conv(dec_val):
  # This function converts a decimal value to minutes (integer) and seconds (integer).
  mins = int(np.floor(dec_val))
  secs = round((dec_val - mins) * 60)
  return [mins, secs]

# Minimum food preparation time (minutes)
fp_min = df2['food_preparation_time'].min()
print('Minimum food preparation time is', fp_min, 'minutes.')

# Mean (average) food preparation time (minutes)
fp_mean = df2['food_preparation_time'].mean()
[fp_mean_min, fp_mean_sec] = min_sec_conv(fp_mean)
print('Mean (average) food preparation time is approximately', fp_mean_min,
      'minutes and', fp_mean_sec, 'seconds.')

# Maximum food preparation time (minutes)
fp_max = df2['food_preparation_time'].max()
print('Maximum food preparation time is', fp_max, 'minutes.')

Minimum food preparation time is 20 minutes.
Mean (average) food preparation time is approximately 27 minutes and 22 seconds.
Maximum food preparation time is 35 minutes.

Observations:¶

The minimum food preparation time is 20 minutes. The mean food preparation time is 27.37197 minutes (approximately 27 minutes and 22 seconds). The maximum food preparation time is 35 minutes.

The next variable we would like to explore is rating.

In [181]:

When Python read in the original CSV file, it classified rating as an "object" type (a categorical variable) because there were "Not given" text values in the column along with the numerical ratings of 3, 4, and 5. I made the decision to change all "Not given" values to NaN, change rating to a float type, and replace the NaN values with the best grouped measure of center possible. In this variable's analysis, I am showing both the old distribution and the new distribution. Most orders were originally not rated, but those that were rated ranged from 3 to 5. It is common for voluntary-response rating scales like this to report extreme dissatisfaction and extreme satisfaction more than middle-of-the-road results. Therefore, "Not given" being the majority is not surprising. What is surprising is that, out of 1,898 orders from 1,200 unique customers, none were ever rated 1 or 2, with a clear left-skewed distribution with a median of 5. Those are very good rating results for FoodHub; so good, that they should consider mentioning that in future marketing and promotional campaigns.

Question 12: Perform a multivariate analysis to explore relationships between the important variables in the dataset. (It is a good idea to explore relations between numerical variables as well as relations between numerical and categorical variables) [10 marks]¶

After observing the correlation values and pairplots between all numerical variables, it is clear that none of these four variables have any significant linear relationships with each other.

Next, we would like to analyze cost_of_the_order, by cuisine_type and day_of_the_week.

In [195]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,7));

The above bar plot shows similar average costs of orders by cuisine type, when compared side-by-side by day of the week. In all but one cuisine type (Spanish), the 95% confidence interval bars for each cuisine type's weekend average cost of order overlaps with its weekday confidence interval. This means that there is not a significant difference in average costs of order for weekends and weekdays. However, with Spanish cuisine, weekend average cost of order significantly exceeds its weekday average.

Now we observe rating, by cuisine_type and day_of_the_week.

In [196]:

Distributions of ratings by cuisine type are all on the higher end of the rating scale. Most range from 3 to 5, and all have median ratings of 4 or higher. Weekend and weekday distributions for most cuisine types are nearly identical. This visualization shows that all cuisine types are highly rated, which is good for FoodHub.

We now continue with an analysis of food_preparation_time, by cuisine_type and day_of_the_week.

In [197]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,7));

plt.xticks(rotation=90);

With this point plot, we can observe each cuisine type's average food preparation time, with their 95% confidence interval estimates. When we compare each cuisine type's weekday confidence interval with its weekend confidence interval, we have overlap (meaning, no significant difference in average food preparation time) for all cuisine types except for Spanish cuisine. With Spanish cuisine, we observe that the weekday average food preparation time is significantly higher than its weekend average. This weekday average for Spanish cuisine is also the highest of all cuisine types, with the lowest averages belonging to Korean and Vietnamese cuisines. Weekend average times show less variation among cuisine types, as weekday average times fluctuate much more for various cuisine types.

Now, let's look at delivery_time, by cuisine_type and day_of_the_week.

In [198]:

plt.xticks(rotation=90);

I originally wanted to show this with a swarm plot, but there were so many points to plot, the only way to fit all points on the plot was to widen the figure size to its maximum horizontal distance AND reduce the point size. This made the plot very hard to see. So, to reduce eye strain, I chose a strip plot instead. This means that there are lots of points here that overlap, but we can still understand the overall insights of the relationships here.

Notice that the distributions of weekend delivery times for each cuisine type show much more variation compared to its corresponding weekday times. While weekday delivery times have less spread in comparison to weekends, its distribution ranges on the higher end of all delivery times represented.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [210]:
# Create function that will calculate FoodHub restaurant charges
def rev(s):
  if s > 20:
    return round(s*0.25, 2) # 25% FoodHub charge (order costs greater than $20)
  elif s > 5 and s <= 20:
    return round(s*0.15, 2) # 15% FoodHub charge (order costs greater than $5 but less than or equal to $20)
  else:
    return 0

# Create new column in data frame for FoodHub's restaurant charges for orders with costs greater than $5
df2['revenue'] = df2['cost_of_the_order'].apply(rev)

# Find total net revenue for FoodHub
total_net_rev = df2['revenue'].sum()
total_net_rev
Out[210]:
6166.5

Observations:¶

FoodHub generates a net revenue of \$6,166.50 across all orders.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • Most customer orders do not get rated. However, those that do are generally rated well. This shows that, when FoodHub customers feel compelled to rate their order experience, the feedback they give is generally positive.
  • The company's promotional offer for restaurants who qualify was a good idea, but in the end, only four out of a total of 178 FoodHub restaurants qualified for the offer.
  • American, Japanese, Italian, and Chinese are the overall favorite cuisine types that FoodHub customers prefer to order.
  • Weekend orders more than double the number of weekday orders.
  • Approximately 70% of all orders cost less than $20.
  • Most FoodHub customers have placed no more than three orders.
  • Food preparation time varies by cuisine type much more on weekdays than on weekends, whereas delivery time varies by cuisine type much more on weekends than on weekdays.
  • Only (approximately) 11% of all orders take more than 60 minutes to be delivered from the time the order is placed.

Recommendations:¶

  • Think of ways to maximize revenue without sacrificing median rating. If approximately 70% of all orders cost less than \$20, but FoodHub receives the largest percentage from restaurants from orders that cost more than $20, then how can FoodHub incentivize customers to place orders that are greater than \$20 as often as possible? Maybe a "Loyalty Program" could be implemented where FoodHub offers customers a free meal after the customer has purchased (for example) 5 meals over \$20. This type of program can help attract new customers, increase the number of orders per customer, increase FoodHub revenue, and increase restaurant revenue, while keeping ratings high.
  • Seek partnerships with more restaurants, but give priority to the cuisine types that are already known to be the most popular among FoodHub customers. These were mentioned earlier as American, Japanese, Italian, and Chinese.
  • Get creative with more customer incentive programs. Giving 20% discount vouchers to the top 5 most frequent customers is a good start, but those only benefit the top 5 customers out of a total of 1200 current customers. Consider making a program with a more randomized design. If all customers feel like they have an equal chance of being selected to benefit from a customer incentive program, then they will feel more motivated to remain active with FoodHub to meet the qualifications of possibly being selected.
  • Also get creative with more restaurant incentive programs. Maybe offer rewards to restaurants that cut down their average food preparation times over a certain period of time.
  • Show your delivery people some love too! They have probably the hardest, thankless jobs of all. If they are happy, then they are motivated to keep FoodHub customers happy, which, of course, is best for business. Consider establishing milestones they can reach for bonuses or raises. These could include (but are not limited to) a certain percentage decrease in average delivery time over a certain period of time, or number of orders delivered with a rating of 4 or above.
  • As mentioned earlier in the univariate analysis, FoodHub should strongly consider mentioning its high ratings in advertisements and other promotions. However, consult a statistician to be sure that the wording and/or visualizations used in those ads are good, accurate, and not misleading.
